// C1: Physical Environment
instance IncubatorEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:contains StyrofoamInsulationContainer, HeatbedComponent, FanComponent
] // Fixed by ensuring component instances exist

// C2: Acting Components
instance HeatbedActuator : DTDFVocab:ActuatingComponent [
    base:desc "Controlled heating element within the styrofoam container that supplies thermal energy to maintain internal temperature"
]

instance FanActuator : DTDFVocab:ActuatingComponent [
    base:desc "Mechanical fan distributing heat uniformly within the insulated incubator environment"
]

// C3: Physical Sensing Components
instance InternalTemperatureSensor1 : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Internal temperature sensor measuring ambient conditions within the styrofoam container (first sensor)"
    DTDFVocab:producedData InternalTempDataStream1
]

instance InternalTemperatureSensor2 : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Internal temperature sensor measuring ambient conditions within the styrofoam container (second sensor)"
    DTDFVocab:producedData InternalTempDataStream2
]

instance ExternalTemperatureSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "External temperature sensor measuring ambient conditions outside the insulated styrofoam container"
    DTDFVocab:producedData ExternalTempDataStream
]

// C4: Data Transmission
instance InternalTempDataStream1 : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom InternalTemperatureSensor1
]

instance InternalTempDataStream2 : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom InternalTemperatureSensor2
]

instance ExternalTempDataStream : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom ExternalTemperatureSensor
]

// C5: Data Components
instance InternalTemperatureData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Real-time numerical temperature readings from internal sensors (Celsius/Kelvin) for state estimation"
    DTDFVocab:fromData InternalTempDataStream1, InternalTempDataStream2
]

instance ExternalTemperatureData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Real-time numerical temperature readings from external sensor for environmental context"
    DTDFVocab:fromData ExternalTempDataStream
]

// C6: Services
instance RealTimeMonitoringService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Continuous streaming of temperature data from internal/external sensors for state estimation and visualization"
    DTDFVocab:provides TemperatureStateInsight
]

instance PredictiveControlService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Dynamic model calibration and predictive simulation of incubator behavior under current/future conditions"
    DTDFVocab:provides TemperatureTrendInsight, OptimizationRecommendationAction
]

instance FaultDetectionService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Anomaly detection and reconfiguration capabilities for thermal imbalances and sensor failures"
    DTDFVocab:provides FaultDetectionInsight, ReconfigurationAction
]

instance HumanMachineInterfaceService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Target setting and feedback loop for user-defined temperature thresholds and system performance metrics"
    DTDFVocab:provides TargetSettingAction, PerformanceFeedbackInsight
]

// C10: Models
instance TwoParameterThermalModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Simplified behavioral model with 2 free parameters capturing basic thermal dynamics (heat transfer coefficients, ambient conditions)"
]

instance FourParameterThermalModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Analytical model with 4 free parameters accounting for thermal inertia of the heatbed for high-fidelity predictions"
]

// C11: Enablers
instance RaspberryPiController : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Central control unit integrating sensor inputs and executing regulatory algorithms via embedded software"
    DTDFVocab:enables RealTimeMonitoringService, PredictiveControlService, FaultDetectionService
]

instance KalmanFilterAlgorithm : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Parameter estimation technique updating thermal models dynamically using sensor data for state estimation"
]

instance LeastSquaresOptimization : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Dynamic calibration algorithm refining model parameters using sensor data for improved accuracy"
]

instance PhysicsSimulationEngine : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Physics-based simulation framework implementing heat transfer equations for predictive simulations"
]

instance StateEstimationAlgorithm : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "State estimation techniques processing sensor data for real-time temperature state assessment"
    DTDFVocab:enables RealTimeMonitoringService
]

instance SupervisoryController : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Higher-level controller managing system reconfiguration and fault handling"
    DTDFVocab:enables FaultDetectionService
]

instance SQLiteDatabase : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Lightweight database storing sensor logs and model parameters for historical analysis"
]

instance ROSCommunicationProtocol : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Real-time communication protocol facilitating seamless data exchange between physical and digital domains"
    DTDFVocab:enables RealTimeMonitoringService, PredictiveControlService
]

instance PythonAutomationLibrary : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Automation library for algorithm development (NumPy, SciPy) enabling fault detection and state estimation"
    DTDFVocab:enables StateEstimationAlgorithm, SupervisoryController
]

// C12: Data Management
instance SensorLogDatabase : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Historical temperature data repository storing sensor readings for model validation and analysis"
    DTDFVocab:fromData InternalTemperatureData, ExternalTemperatureData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SQLiteDatabase
]

// C13: Twinning Process
instance CalibrationFeedbackLoop : DTDFVocab:Process [
    base:desc "Closed-loop structure where sensor data feeds into model calibration algorithms for continuous refinement"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo KalmanFilterAlgorithm, LeastSquaresOptimization
    DTDFVocab:outputTo TwoParameterThermalModel, FourParameterThermalModel
]

instance ExperimentalValidationProcess : DTDFVocab:Process [
    base:desc "Validation of DT performance against physical twin outcomes through real-world experiments"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo FourParameterThermalModel
    DTDFVocab:outputTo PerformanceFeedbackInsight
]

// Define missing instances
instance TemperatureStateInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Real-time temperature state assessment of the incubator system"
]

instance AnomalyDetectionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Detection of temperature anomalies and thermal imbalances"
]

instance TemperatureTrendInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Predicted temperature trends and future state estimations"
]

instance OptimizationRecommendationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Recommendations for optimal fan/heatbed configuration to maintain target temperature"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance FaultDetectionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Detection of sensor failures and thermal system anomalies"
]

instance ReconfigurationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated system reconfiguration to address thermal imbalances"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance TargetSettingAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "User-defined target temperature setting for the incubator"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic false
]

instance PerformanceFeedbackInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "System performance metrics and feedback for user evaluation"
]

instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "
  The virtual-to-physical interaction in the incubator DT involves **control commands** generated by the digital model to regulate the physical incubator. The system uses a **Raspberry Pi-based controller** to execute these commands, which include:
  - **Heating power adjustments** (via the heatbed) to maintain target temperature
  - **Fan speed modulation** (for heat distribution) based on thermal feedback
  The control message formats are not explicitly detailed, but the system employs **state estimators** (implied by Document 1) to validate virtual commands before execution. Feedback mechanisms involve real-time temperature monitoring (via sensors) to detect deviations from setpoints, triggering recalibration or reoptimization of control algorithms. Command execution is confirmed through **closed-loop control** where the DT adjusts parameters dynamically to ensure physical twin compliance with virtual predictions.
 "
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "
  The Digital Twin (DT) for the incubator system operates with **real-time synchronization** between the physical and digital twins, leveraging the **Raspberry Pi** as the central controller. The temporal granularity is tied to the **sampling frequency of temperature sensors** (two internal and one external), which are likely synchronized at **low-to-mid frequency ranges (e.g., 1 Hz to 10 Hz)** based on typical sensor protocols (e.g., I2C or SPI) and the system’s thermal dynamics. The DT employs **calibration algorithms** (as depicted in Fig. 1) to update models dynamically, ensuring alignment with the physical twin’s operational state. Latency requirements are implicit but inferred from the need for **real-time control** (e.g., temperature regulation) and **model calibration** to reflect the **thermal inertia** of the heatbed and insulated container. The system’s time scale is optimized for **short-term predictive accuracy** (e.g., seconds to minutes) rather than long-term forecasting, given the focus on immediate temperature stabilization.
  "
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "
  The Digital Twin constellation for the incubator follows a **monolithic cyber-physical architecture**, where the **Raspberry Pi** serves as the core cyber component interfacing with the physical plant (styrofoam box, heatbed, fan, and sensors). The DT integrates **two distinct simulation models** (one with 2 free parameters, one with 4) for temperature prediction, calibrated via real-time data from the PT. The orchestration involves:
  - **Model calibration loops** (as shown in Fig. 1) that update parameters dynamically using sensor data.
  - **Monitoring and supervisory control** (e.g., fault detection, state estimation) to ensure system safety and optimal performance.
  - **No explicit mention of advanced orchestration patterns** (e.g., microservices, cloud-based orchestration) beyond the Raspberry Pi’s role. The system’s coordination is **hardware-centric**, relying on embedded software and sensor networks for real-time decision-making.
  "
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "
  **Lifecycle Phases of Digital Twin (DT) as inferred from the documents:**
  - **Development Phase:**
    - **Initial Modeling:** Creation of abstract representations (e.g., CAD models, dynamic models via differential equations) to understand system behavior at different abstraction levels.
    - **Model Calibration:** Integration of models with real-time data from the Physical Twin (PT) to refine parameters (e.g., using calibration algorithms as depicted in Document 1, Figure 1).

  - **Operational Phase:**
    - **Continuous Monitoring:** Real-time data collection from sensors (e.g., temperature sensors in the incubator case study) to observe PT behavior under current conditions.
    - **Simulation & Prediction:** Running simulations to reproduce and predict PT behavior dynamically (e.g., for temperature regulation in the incubator).

  - **Optimization & Adaptation Phase:**
    - **Data-Driven Adjustments:** Use of algorithms (e.g., fault detectors, state estimators) to detect violations (e.g., temperature deviations) and trigger corrective actions (human or automated).
    - **Reconfigurability:** Adaptive adjustments to models/algorithms based on changing environments (e.g., robustness in the incubator’s temperature regulation).

  - **Lifecycle Governance:**
    - **Integration with PT:** Models are retained and integrated into DT frameworks post-deployment (Document 1), ensuring persistence and evolution.
    - **Abstraction Levels:** Models exist at varying levels of detail (e.g., high-level CAD vs. low-level dynamic equations), with trade-offs between accuracy and computational efficiency.
    - **Transition Management:** Calibration and iterative updates bridge the gap between static models and dynamic PT behavior (e.g., recalibration loops in Figure 1).

  **Note:** The documents do not explicitly outline formal lifecycle governance frameworks (e.g., ISO standards) or explicit phase transitions, but the described stages align with common DT lifecycle models (e.g., design → deployment → operation → optimization).
  "
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "
**Model Fidelity Requirements**:
- **Thermal Inertia**: Critical for accurate predictions; the **4-parameter model** explicitly addresses this via additional parameters (e.g., heatbed-specific thermal properties).
- **Dynamic Behavior**: Models incorporate differential equations (Section 5, [3]) to simulate transient responses under varying conditions.

**Validation/Verification Methods**:
- **Experimental Validation**: The incubator case study uses **open-source hardware/software** to empirically test model performance (4-parameter model outperforms baseline).
- **Uncertainty Quantification**: Implied via **calibration algorithms** that iteratively refine model parameters using sensor data.

**Error Detection/Correction**:
- **Monitors**: Real-time checks for deviations between PT and DT behavior (e.g., fault detectors flagging thermal anomalies).
- **Automated Adjustments**: Algorithms (e.g., state estimators) dynamically correct model parameters based on sensor feedback.

**Quality Assurance**:
- **Model Calibration**: Continuous updates via **closed-loop calibration** (data → models → monitors → PT adjustments).
- **Hardware/Software Accessibility**: Open-source platform ensures reproducibility and verifiability of techniques.
"
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "
  The DT's technical network infrastructure for the incubator relies on a **CPS-based architecture** where:
  - **Communication protocols** are not explicitly named, but the system leverages **embedded computing (Raspberry Pi)** and **networked sensors** for real-time data exchange.
  - **Network topology** is a **point-to-point** structure between the physical sensors, Raspberry Pi controller, and DT simulation environment (likely local/edge deployment).
  - **Bandwidth and latency requirements** are implied by the need for **real-time temperature monitoring and control** (critical for thermal regulation). The system prioritizes **low-latency communication** to ensure timely feedback loops.
  - **Reliability and redundancy mechanisms** are not detailed, but the DT includes **calibration algorithms** (Document 1) to handle sensor drift and model inaccuracies, ensuring robustness against environmental variations.
  - **Security protocols** are not mentioned, but the DT framework (Document 1) integrates **algorithms for data validation and anomaly detection**, suggesting basic cybersecurity measures are applied to protect against unauthorized access or data corruption.
 "
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "
  The DT for the incubator is deployed on a **local/edge infrastructure** (Raspberry Pi-based CPS), with no explicit mention of cloud or distributed hosting. The computational requirements include:
  - **Real-time processing** of sensor data and control algorithms (implied by the need for dynamic temperature regulation).
  - **Storage requirements** are not specified, but the DT integrates **models with calibration parameters** (Document 4) and simulation outputs, suggesting persistent storage for historical data and model versions.
  - **Scalability mechanisms** are not detailed, but the DT supports **reconfigurability** (Document 2) to adapt to changing environmental conditions (e.g., content inside the incubator).
  - **Deployment models** are likely **on-premise/edge deployment**, given the CPS architecture and lack of cloud references. The system ensures **availability/reliability** through **closed-loop control** and **calibration algorithms** (Document 1) to maintain synchronization between the physical and virtual twins.
  "
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "
  **Standardization and Compliance:**
  - **Relevant Standards:**
    - **Industry-Specific:** Aligns with **Industry 4.0** principles (e.g., digital integration, real-time monitoring) but lacks explicit references to formal standards like **ISO 23247 (Digital Twin)** or **IEC 62264** (IT integration in manufacturing).
    - **Related Frameworks:** Overlaps with **self-adaptive systems**, **autonomic computing**, and **models@runtime** (Document 2), but no direct standardization is mentioned.

  - **Specifications:**
    - **Open-Source Repository:** Publicly available hardware/software specs (e.g., [GitHub incubator repo](https://github.com/INTO-CPS-Association/example-incubator)) enable interoperability but lack formal compliance documentation.

  - **Certification/Compliance:**
    - **None Explicitly Mentioned:** The documents do not reference certification bodies (e.g., ISO, IEC) or compliance frameworks for DTs.

  - **Interoperability:**
    - **Technical Interoperability:** DTs in the incubator case study integrate with CPS (Cyber-Physical Systems) tools (e.g., Raspberry Pi) but no standards (e.g., OPC UA, MQTT) are explicitly cited.

  **Note:** The documents describe **emerging practices** without formal standardization, suggesting a gap in compliance frameworks for DTs in this context.
  "
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin (DT) system for the incubator case study integrates cyber-physical security measures to ensure safe and reliable operation. The system employs a **Raspberry Pi**-based control architecture to monitor and regulate temperature within an insulated styrofoam container, utilizing **two internal temperature sensors** and **one external sensor** for environmental data acquisition. While the documents do not explicitly detail explicit security protocols (e.g., encryption, access control), the DT relies on **calibration algorithms** to update cyber-physical models dynamically, ensuring robustness against environmental variations. The system’s **fail-safe mechanisms** are implied through its **reconfigurability** (e.g., adjusting heating/fan distribution to maintain target temperature), which enhances safety by mitigating deviations. The DT’s **monitoring subsystem** detects deviations from optimal performance, triggering automated or human interventions to prevent critical failures. The hardware setup (e.g., sensors, insulated container) inherently supports safety by reducing thermal losses, but no explicit risk assessment or compliance frameworks (e.g., ISO 27001, IEC 62443) are mentioned. The DT’s **predictive capabilities** (via simulations) enable proactive safety checks, though no specific threat mitigation strategies (e.g., intrusion detection) are described."
]